AFTER much deliberation, axed Bafana Bafana head coach Ephraim &ldquo;Shakes&rdquo; Mashaba will know the outcome of his arbitration hearing on 7 March.Mashaba was fired by the South African Football Association (Safa) in December after being found guilty by the association&rsquo;s disciplinary committee of gross misconduct, insubordination and bringing Safa into disrepute.Mashaba failed in his bid to get reinstated as Bafana Bafana head coach after a hearing by the Commission for Conciliation, Mediation and Arbitration last week and his lawyer, Claudio Bollo, opted to take the matter to arbitration.Safa spokesman Dominic Chimhavi confirmed yesterday that the arbitration hearing with Mashaba had been set for 7 March.He said: &ldquo;The arbitration will be final and binding for both parties, and that will be the end of the matter.&rdquo;Chimhavi said they were confident of a positive outcome at the arbitration hearing: &ldquo;Safa has done everything with regard to the Mashaba case by the book.&rdquo;He also stressed that it was all systems go in looking for a successor for Mashaba: &ldquo;The Safa NEC (National Executive Committee) took a decision at the weekend to search for a new Bafana head coach and we are working hard towards that goal.&ldquo;It is important to have the new coach in place next month before we play in two friendly international games on the Fifa dates in March.&rdquo;Bafana have a busy schedule for 2017, with 2019 Africa Cup of Nations qualifiers kicking off in June, African Nations Championship qualifiers in July and August, plus the resumption of the 2018 World Cup qualifiers in September.Safa has been flooded with CVs from coaches from all over the world but Safa president Danny Jordaan said at the weekend that they would head-hunt a new Bafana head coach, not advertise the post.